04170nam a22004695i 9780226996981DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20211988ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226996981  a(DE-B1597)575473  a(OCoLC)1248759783  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aQH318 ǂb Z97 1988eb 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a574.02211 aZweifel, Frances W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Handbook of Biological Illustration /cFrances W. Zweifel. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©1988  a1 online resource (152 p.) :bll halftones, 57 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChicago Guides to Writing, Editing, and Publishing00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- t1 Printing Processes -- t2 Size and Reduction of Illustrations for Publication -- t3 Materials -- t4 The Preliminary Drawings -- t5 The Finished Drawing -- t6 Preparing Graphs and Maps -- t7 Lettering -- t8 Poster Sessions -- t9 Photographs, Plates, and Projection Slides -- t10 Mounting and Packing Illustrations -- tAfterword -- tSelected References -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book is designed to help biologists who must create their own illustrations and artists who are confronted with unfamiliar biological subjects. The author, an experienced biological illustrator, gives practical instructions and advice on the consideration of size and of printing processes, choice of materials, methods for saving time and labor, drawing techniques, lettering methods, and mounting and packing the finished illustrations. She explains how to produce clear and attractive charts, graphs, and maps, so essential to science publications. Though this primer does not cover photographic techniques, it does include advice on retouching, cropping, and mounting photographs and on using photographs of biological subjects as aids in drawing. This second edition is updated to reflect the many technological changes in art materials and printing processes that have occurred since the book's first publication, and it includes an entirely new chapter on planning, designing, and mounting the poster presentations that have become an essential part of conferences held by scientific societies. Also included are the requirements and conventions peculiar to biological illustration and a bibliography of useful reference works. "Every biology student who intends to write a thesis deserves to own this book, as does the biologist who intends to publish or work up some visual aids for his own use. There is no reason to limit the concepts of this handbook to the field of biology; it should be useful to other specific areas of science."—Evan Lindquist, American Biology Teacher (from a review of the first edition)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBiological illustration. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  abiology, illustrations, art, research, publishing, publication, size, printing, materials, drawing techniques, lettering, mounting, packing, charts, graphs, maps, science, scholarship, academia, nonfiction, reference, manual, guide, retouching, cropping, photography, poster presentations, conferences, design, graduate student, thesis, dissertation, graphics, plates, projection slides.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226996981423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226996981/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles